item.title: RC Plane snow Ski
item.description:
Skis for your planes so you can fly in the frozen winter! I live in Maine, so flying in the winter time means snow. Obviously, skis had to happen. I've tweaked these to the point that I'm pretty happy with them. They look scale-ish and fly well. The only thing I'd say is that when landing, you might need more up elevator than you're used to.

They are designed to be held on with rubber bands over the wheels ans "sprung" with either a cut rubber band or elastic thread for the front and back to keep the skis at the correct attitude. Be sure to take them off when you're done flying so the rubber bands don't deform your tires.

I printed these in PEGP but I can't see how it wouldn't work in PLA. Supports are only for the lugs that the rubber bands fit over to keep it on the wheel. I've been flying with these for two winters now and they work really well. These were designed to fit 70mmx20mm wheels (2.75 in x .75 in) but can be scaled easily to fit smaller wheels.

item.title: Sydney City cityscape with topography- 16 tiles
item.description:
Plesase note I am yet to print this myself but have tested slicing each individual tile and it slices fine. You will need to add a model of the Harbour Bridge. there are numerous free models to choose from on Thingiverse.

I created this using OpenStreetData. © OpenStreetMap contributors. data is available under the Open Database License. https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright

I have scaled all tiles equally and up 150% to exaggerate the buildings, you may want to scale them down. All tiles are made to fit on a standard ender 3 v2 bed. I created this because I am tight and didn't want to pay someone for it. There were no detailed free versions I could find. Enjoy

item.title: Yeti 14 oz Rambler Adapter for 2017 Toyota Tacoma Center Console Middle Cup Holder
item.description:
A family member wanted an adapter for their cup holder so that it could hold their 14 oz Yeti Rambler and its hot coffee safe during their morning commute.

A lot of the existing designs did not allow for printing without supports or limited how the cup could be oriented.

This design hopes to solve that by making it easy to print and easy to place the cup. Designed with a 0.4 mm nozzle in mind with a wall thickness of 4.8 mm. The handle slot number can be increased, but i recommend around 7 as a max. 60degree overhangs max.

This model works well for the center console cup holder of a 2017 Toyota Tacoma, but may work well with other cup holders that have a ~70 mm bottom ID, ~80 mm top ID, and a 80 mm height. If you try this print and it works well with your car please let me know and I can add it to the list so others can be aware.
Year-Make-Model Cup Holder Location
2017 Toyota Tacoma Middle Center Console
…pending… …pending…

If you want the Yeti Rambler dimensions to make your own accessories, I uploaded it to my profile as a separate print.

IMPORTANT!

If you planning on printing these files please be aware of what temperatures can be reached inside your vehicle during the summer months. I would highly recommend printing in PETG rather than PLA.

item.title: Butted Goblin Fairy
item.description:
Have you ever wished you had a little Goblin with a butt to share your space with and look deeply into the eyes of the all knowing? Well your in luck because here it is!

Print it
Look at its butt
Be happy!

Recommendations for printing:

Super straight forward, prints without supports. I would recommend dialing in your retraction settings, and making sure your filament is dry for the horns to come out well!

Also if your slicing in Cura and printing at 100%, enabling the setting "filter out tiny gaps" will help print the horns smoother, not sure if this still applies once it is resized.

Enjoy!

item.title: Xu-Ha Lancer Cruiser
item.description:
My interpretation of one of the First Ones races, Xu-Ha.

Xu-Ha Lancer Cruiser based on graphics on Babylon 5 Wars supplement, from Steam https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=1521518042.

Race description from "Darkness & Light" by Mongoose Publishing:

"The Xu-Ha were one of the most advanced and respected species in the galaxy. They had been one of the chief architects of the post-Speaker galactic peace and while they
were not nearly as universally respected as the Speakers, they were beloved by many."

"Transcendence drove the race mad. This madness was a slow cultural tide that took millennia to truly manifest. The Xu-Ha had failed as a Third Age race; without the Speakers to guide them, they were adrift. For no apparent reason, the Xu-Ha began purging the galaxy of lesser races. Their actions were subtle, involving hidden machines that blasted out psychic pulses. Other First One races offered the Xu-Ha a chance
to stop their campaign of genocide. The Xu-Ha refused this offer, and consequently other First Ones annihilated the Xu-Ha."

Intended for FDM printing. Extrude thin parts and scale before printing.

item.title: Micro Swiss ADXL345 Hotend Mount
item.description:
This is a mount for an ADXL345 accelerometer to test resonance frequencies on the X axis. It attaches to the Micro Swiss hot end to give a more accurate reading of the resonance frequencies at the extruder tip.

Requires 4x m3 screws, either 4mm or 5mm.

Might fit on other hotends, but might require some tweaking to fit. Remove hot end sock before use.

item.title: Elevation Supports
item.description:
A must-have for that sprawling multi-level dungeon. If you've been having fun with printable terrain in your game, but want to display the larger layout as a complete map, these will do the trick.

These supports are made for floor tiles and walls of the OpenLock system. They're stackable and the clips are removable for a future model. (The current clips don't fit the newer tessellation versions. I'll be putting out those soon.) Depending on how many you use, you can greatly increase stability. There is also a Base Support for extra stability.

Note: the clips are intended to snap in with the bump away from the beveled side of the support. It'll go in either way, but it's more secure.

item.title: flopping fish automaton
item.description:
The goal of this project was to design a 3D-printed automaton according to our own imagination and other automaton inspirations online. Once all parts were assembled to the best of our capability, we tested to see how they worked and post-processed our parts to have the automaton function.

Our project is a 3D printed flopping fish. We created a box 20cm long that fit the fish's body parts. Through the use of eight cams, we were able to create a repetitive bouncing motion. My partner and I hand-designed each part prior to 3D design to find appropriate dimensions for all parts of the automaton.
